Ukraine’s Gross External Debt Rises on Eurobond, Weaker Hryvnia

-- B y   D a r y n a   K r a s n o l u t s k a
-- 
2011-06-17T15:28:32Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-17/ukraine-s-gross-external-debt-rises-on-eurobond-weaker-hryvnia.html
Ukraine’s gross external debt rose
2.7 percent in the first quarter as the country sold Eurobonds
and the hryvnia fell against the euro, the central bank said.  Debt totaled $120.5 billion as of April 1, compared with
$117.3 billion three months earlier, the Kiev-based  Natsionalnyi
Bank Ukrainy  said today in a statement on its website.  The government’s foreign debt jumped to $26 billion from
$25 billion in the period, according to the statement.
International borrowing by the nation’s banks rose to $28.2
billion from $28.1 billion, the data shows. External debt due
within 12 months totaled $51 billion, compared with $49.3
billion on Jan. 1, the data showed.  Some 69.4 percent of international debt was denominated in
dollars, with 11.2 percent in euros. The hryvnia gained 0.2
percent against the dollar during the quarter and fell 5.7
percent against the euro.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Daryna Krasnolutska in Kiev at 
